  "doc_id": "18420",
  "text": "Nitrous oxide (N 2 O) is a stable greenhouse gas in the troposphere and is involved directly in global warming. In the stratosphere it is responsible for the catalytic decomposition of ozone [CITATION_1] . The increase in the atmosphere is reported at present to be about 0.25% per year (IPCC, 2001) . As the potential of global warming of N 2 O is 300 times higher than that of carbon dioxide (CO 2 ) a further increase of atmospheric N 2 O concentration might affect global climate even more in the future.",
